   "source": [
    "# Understanding Figure and Axes in Matplotlib\n",
    "**Author:** Hamna Munir\n",
    "**Repository:** Python-Libraries-for-AI-ML\n",
    "\n",
    "This notebook introduces the core structure of Matplotlib: **Figure** and **Axes**.\n",
    "\n",
    "Understanding these two components is essential for working with Matplotlib’s object-oriented interface, which provides more control and flexibility compared to using simple functions like `plt.plot()`.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "## 1. Introduction\n",
    "Matplotlib is built around a hierarchical architecture. The two most important building blocks are:\n",
    "\n",
    "### 1. Figure\n",
    "- The overall container for everything you see in a plot.\n",
    "- It can hold multiple subplots (Axes), legends, titles, images, etc.\n",
    "- Think of it as the **canvas**.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 2. Axes\n",
    "- The actual area where data is plotted.\n",
    "- Each Axes contains:\n",
    "  - The x-axis\n",
    "  - The y-axis\n",
    "  - Labels\n",
    "  - Plot lines and markers\n",
    "- Think of it as the **drawing area**.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "## 2. Why Use the Object-Oriented (OO) Interface?\n",
    "The OO interface is recommended for:\n",
    "- Complex plots\n",
    "- Multiple subplots\n",
    "- Professional visualization\n",
    "- Dashboard-style figure layouts\n",
    "\n",
    "The OO approach avoids confusion and gives better control than using the stateful `plt` interface.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "metadata": {},
   "execution_count": null,
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "%matplotlib inline"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## 3. Creating a Figure and Axes\n",
    "The recommended way to create a plot is:\n",
    "\n",
    "### `fig, ax = plt.subplots()`\n",
    "\n",
    "- `fig` → the Figure object\n",
    "- `ax` → the Axes object\n",
    "\n",
    "This method automatically creates a figure and a single set of axes."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "metadata": {},
   "execution_count": null,
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(7, 4))\n",
    "\n",
    "ax.plot([1, 2, 3], [2, 4, 6])\n",
    "ax.set_title(\"Basic Figure and Axes Example\")\n",
    "ax.set_xlabel(\"X-axis\")\n",
    "ax.set_ylabel(\"Y-axis\")\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## 4. Understanding the Role of Figure\n",
    "The **Figure** is the main container for the entire visualization.\n",
    "\n",
    "It controls:\n",
    "- Overall size of the plot\n",
    "- DPI (resolution)\n",
    "- Multiple Axes (subplots)\n",
    "- Saving the figure (`fig.savefig(\"file.png\")`)\n",
    "\n",
    "Example: Setting a custom figure size and DPI."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "metadata": {},
   "execution_count": null,
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "fig = plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5), dpi=120)\n",
    "ax = fig.add_subplot(1, 1, 1)\n",
    "ax.plot([0, 1, 2], [0, 1, 4])\n",
    "ax.set_title(\"Figure Size and DPI Example\")\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## 5. Understanding Axes in Detail\n",
    "\n",
    "Axes is the most important component in Matplotlib because **your actual plot is drawn on it**.\n",
    "\n",
    "Each Axes contains:\n",
    "- Titles\n",
    "- X/Y labels\n",
    "- Ticks and tick labels\n",
    "- Lines, scatter points, bars, etc.\n",
    "- Grid lines\n",
    "\n",
    "Axes also provide setter and getter functions such as:\n",
    "- `ax.set_title()`\n",
    "- `ax.set_xlabel()`\n",
    "- `ax.set_ylabel()`\n",
    "- `ax.set_xlim()`\n",
    "- `ax.set_ylim()`\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "metadata": {},
   "execution_count": null,
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(7, 4))\n",
    "\n",
    "ax.plot([1, 2, 3, 4], [3, 8, 2, 10])\n",
    "ax.set_title(\"Axes Customization Example\")\n",
    "ax.set_xlabel(\"Input\")\n",
    "ax.set_ylabel(\"Output\")\n",
    "ax.grid(True)\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## 6. Multiple Axes in a Single Figure\n",
    "A single Figure can contain **multiple Axes**, making it useful for subplot layouts.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Creating multiple Axes:\n",
    "`fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2)` → 1 row, 2 columns\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "metadata": {},
   "execution_count": null,
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(10, 4))\n",
    "\n",
    "axes[0].plot([1, 2, 3], [2, 3, 5])\n",
    "axes[0].set_title(\"Left Plot\")\n",
    "\n",
    "axes[1].plot([1, 2, 3], [5, 3, 1])\n",
    "axes[1].set_title(\"Right Plot\")\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## 7. Manually Adding Axes (Advanced)\n",
    "You can manually place an Axes inside a Figure using:\n",
    "\n",
    "`fig.add_axes([left, bottom, width, height])`\n",
    "\n",
    "Values range from 0 to 1 as a percentage of the Figure size.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "metadata": {},
   "execution_count": null,
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "fig = plt.figure(figsize=(7, 4))\n",
    "ax = fig.add_axes([0.1, 0.1, 0.8, 0.8])\n",
    "\n",
    "ax.plot([0, 1], [0, 1])\n",
    "ax.set_title(\"Manually Positioned Axes\")\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## 8. Common Mistake: Confusing Figure and Axes\n",
    "Beginners often confuse Figure and Axes.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Correct Understanding:\n",
    "```\n",
    "Figure → Whole window or page\n",
    "Axes   → Plotting area inside the Figure\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "A Figure can contain 1 or many Axes.\n",
    "\n",
    "Each Axes is an independent plotting area."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
